        {"id": "h2", "text": "Cell lines with `egfr_amplification == 1` have more negative `dependency_EGFR` scores than cell lines with `egfr_amplification == 0`, after adjusting for lineage and screen covariates.", "kind": "novel"},
        {"id": "h3", "text": "Cell lines with `erbb2_amplification == 1` have more negative `dependency_ERBB2` scores than cell lines with `erbb2_amplification == 0`, after adjusting for lineage and screen covariates.", "kind": "novel"},
        {"id": "h4", "text": "Cell lines with `kras_mutation == 1` have more negative `dependency_KRAS` scores than cell lines with `kras_mutation == 0`, after adjusting for lineage and screen covariates.", "kind": "novel"}
      ],
      "analyses": [
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h1"], "code": "OLS: dependency_BRAF ~ braf_v600e + C(lineage) + C(screen_batch) + C(culture_type) + C(media_serum_pct) + cas9_activity_score + growth_rate_doublings_per_day", "result_summary": "Adjusted `braf_v600e` coefficient was -0.5545 dependency-score units, indicating markedly stronger BRAF dependency in BRAF V600E cell lines.", "effect_estimate": -0.554513, "p_value": 0.0, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h2"], "code": "OLS: dependency_EGFR ~ egfr_amplification + C(lineage) + screen/culture/media/cas9/growth covariates", "result_summary": "Adjusted `egfr_amplification` coefficient was -0.3489, supporting EGFR amplification as the dominant EGFR-dependency feature.", "effect_estimate": -0.348920, "p_value": 0.0, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h3"], "code": "OLS: dependency_ERBB2 ~ erbb2_amplification + C(lineage) + screen/culture/media/cas9/growth covariates", "result_summary": "Adjusted `erbb2_amplification` coefficient was -0.4325, supporting strong ERBB2 dependency in ERBB2-amplified lines.", "effect_estimate": -0.432533, "p_value": 0.0, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h4"], "code": "OLS: dependency_KRAS ~ kras_mutation + C(lineage) + screen/culture/media/cas9/growth covariates", "result_summary": "Adjusted `kras_mutation` coefficient was -0.3095, supporting KRAS-mutant selective KRAS dependency.", "effect_estimate": -0.309546, "p_value": 0.0, "significant": True}
      ]
    },
    {
      "index": 2,
      "proposed_hypotheses": [
        {"id": "h5", "text": "Among cell lines with `braf_v600e == 1`, `lineage == skin` cell lines have more negative `dependency_BRAF` scores than non-skin BRAF V600E cell lines.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h6", "text": "Among cell lines with `kras_mutation == 1`, `lineage == pancreatic` cell lines have more negative `dependency_KRAS` scores than non-pancreatic KRAS-mutant cell lines.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h7", "text": "Cell lines with both `egfr_amplification == 1` and `lineage == brain` have more negative `dependency_EGFR` scores than all other cell lines.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h8", "text": "Cell lines with both `erbb2_amplification == 1` and `lineage == breast` have more negative `dependency_ERBB2` scores than all other cell lines.", "kind": "refined"}
      ],
      "analyses": [
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h5"], "code": "Welch test within braf_v600e == 1; also OLS interaction dependency_BRAF ~ braf_v600e * I(lineage == '"'skin') + screen covariates\", \"result_summary\": \"Within BRAF V600E lines, skin lines were only -0.0103 units more negative than non-skin lines (p=0.295), and the BRAF V600E by skin interaction was not significant (interaction -0.0128, p=0.282).\", \"effect_estimate\": -0.0103, \"p_value\": 0.295, \"significant\": False, \"interaction_effect_estimate\": -0.0128, \"interaction_p_value\": 0.282},
        {\"hypothesis_ids\": [\"h6\"], \"code\": \"Welch test within kras_mutation == 1; also OLS interaction dependency_KRAS ~ kras_mutation * I(lineage == 'pancreatic') + screen covariates\", \"result_summary\": \"Within KRAS-mutant lines, pancreatic lines were not more KRAS dependent than non-pancreatic KRAS-mutant lines (effect +0.0004, p=0.955); the interaction was also null (-0.0025, p=0.818).\", \"effect_estimate\": 0.0004, \"p_value\": 0.955, \"significant\": False, \"interaction_effect_estimate\": -0.0025, \"interaction_p_value\": 0.818},
        {\"hypothesis_ids\": [\"h7\"], \"code\": \"OLS: dependency_EGFR ~ I(egfr_amplification == 1 and lineage == 'brain') + screen/media/cas9/growth covariates\", \"result_summary\": \"The EGFR-amplified brain subgroup (n=815) had more negative "'`dependency_EGFR` than all other lines; adjusted subgroup coefficient was -0.3370.", "effect_estimate": -0.336967, "p_value": 2.69e-155, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h8"], "code": "OLS: dependency_ERBB2 ~ I(erbb2_amplification == 1 and lineage == '"'breast') + screen/media/cas9/growth covariates\", \"result_summary\": \"The ERBB2-amplified breast subgroup (n=1121) had more negative "'`dependency_ERBB2` than all other lines; adjusted subgroup coefficient was -0.4158.", "effect_estimate": -0.415794, "p_value": 2.4e-301, "significant": True}
      ]
    },
    {
      "index": 3,
      "proposed_hypotheses": [
        {"id": "h9", "text": "Cell lines with `nf1_loss == 1` have more negative `dependency_RIT1` scores than cell lines with `nf1_loss == 0`, after adjusting for lineage and screen covariates.", "kind": "novel"},
        {"id": "h10", "text": "The subgroup with both `nf1_loss == 1` and `lineage == brain` has especially negative `dependency_RIT1` scores, and `lineage == brain` enhances the NF1-loss effect on RIT1 dependency.", "kind": "refined"}
      ],
      "analyses": [
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h9"], "code": "OLS: dependency_RIT1 ~ nf1_loss + C(lineage) + screen/culture/media/cas9/growth covariates", "result_summary": "Adjusted `nf1_loss` coefficient was -0.0955, supporting stronger RIT1 dependency in NF1-loss lines.", "effect_estimate": -0.095464, "p_value": 6.13e-69, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h10"], "code": "OLS subgroup indicator and interaction: dependency_RIT1 ~ nf1_loss * I(lineage == '"'brain') + screen covariates\", \"result_summary\": \"The NF1-loss brain subgroup (n=329) had adjusted effect -0.1384 vs all other lines (p=9.58e-13). The NF1-loss by brain interaction was -0.0579 (p=0.00582), indicating brain lineage enhances the NF1-loss RIT1 dependency.\", \"effect_estimate\": -0.138408, \"p_value\": 9.58e-13, \"significant\": True, \"interaction_effect_estimate\": -0.0579, \"interaction_p_value\": 0.00582}
      ]
    },
    {
      \"index\": 4,
      \"proposed_hypotheses\": [
        {\"id\": \"h11\", \"text\": \"Cell lines with "'`apc_mutation == 1` have more negative `dependency_KIF18A` scores than cell lines with `apc_mutation == 0`, after adjusting for lineage and screen covariates.", "kind": "novel"},
        {"id": "h12", "text": "Higher `wnt_activity_score` is associated with more negative `dependency_KIF18A` scores, after adjusting for lineage and screen covariates.", "kind": "novel"},
        {"id": "h13", "text": "Cell lines with `lineage == colorectal`, `apc_mutation == 1`, and high `wnt_activity_score` (top quartile, `wnt_activity_score >= 0.819`) have much more negative `dependency_KIF18A` scores than all other cell lines.", "kind": "refined"}
      ],
      "analyses": [
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h11"], "code": "OLS: dependency_KIF18A ~ apc_mutation + C(lineage) + screen/culture/media/cas9/growth covariates", "result_summary": "Adjusted `apc_mutation` coefficient was -0.1469, supporting an APC-associated KIF18A dependency signal.", "effect_estimate": -0.146867, "p_value": 5.85e-180, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h12"], "code": "OLS: dependency_KIF18A ~ z(wnt_activity_score) + C(lineage) + screen/culture/media/cas9/growth covariates", "result_summary": "Each 1-SD increase in `wnt_activity_score` was associated with a -0.0440 change in `dependency_KIF18A`.", "effect_estimate": -0.044030, "p_value": 1.14e-113, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h13"], "code": "OLS subgroup indicator: dependency_KIF18A ~ I(lineage == '"'colorectal' and apc_mutation == 1 and wnt_activity_score >= Q75) + screen/media/cas9/growth covariates\", \"result_summary\": \"The colorectal/APC-mutant/high-WNT subgroup (n=3133) was very strongly KIF18A dependent, with adjusted subgroup coefficient -0.8596.\", \"effect_estimate\": -0.859627, \"p_value\": 0.0, \"significant\": True}
      ]
    },
    {
      \"index\": 5,
      \"proposed_hypotheses\": [
        {\"id\": \"h14\", \"text\": \"Within the "'`lineage == colorectal`, `apc_mutation == 1`, high-`wnt_activity_score` subgroup, `smad4_loss == 1` suppresses KIF18A dependency, so the complete strongest subgroup is `lineage == colorectal`, `apc_mutation == 1`, high `wnt_activity_score`, and `smad4_loss == 0`.", "kind": "refined"}
      ],
      "analyses": [
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h14"], "code": "Welch test within colorectal/APC/high-WNT subgroup comparing smad4_loss == 1 vs smad4_loss == 0", "result_summary": "Within colorectal/APC-mutant/high-WNT lines, `smad4_loss == 1` shifted `dependency_KIF18A` upward by +1.0433 (less dependent): mean -0.2557 with SMAD4 loss vs -1.2990 with SMAD4 intact.", "effect_estimate": 1.0433, "p_value": 0.0, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h14"], "code": "Welch test for complete subgroup I(lineage == '"'colorectal' and apc_mutation == 1 and wnt_activity_score >= Q75 and smad4_loss == 0) vs all other lines\", \"result_summary\": \"The complete SMAD4-intact colorectal/APC-mutant/high-WNT subgroup (n=2571) had mean "'`dependency_KIF18A` -1.2990 vs -0.2530 in all other lines, effect -1.0460.", "effect_estimate": -1.045960, "p_value": 0.0, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h14"], "code": "OLS interaction: dependency_KIF18A ~ I(colorectal/APC/high-WNT) * smad4_loss + screen covariates", "result_summary": "The interaction between the colorectal/APC/high-WNT subgroup and `smad4_loss` was +1.0393 (p underflowed to 0), confirming that SMAD4 loss suppresses the dependency.", "effect_estimate": 1.0393, "p_value": 0.0, "significant": True}
      ]
    },
    {
      "index": 6,
      "proposed_hypotheses": [
        {"id": "h15", "text": "Cell lines with `myc_amplification == 1` have more negative `dependency_RPL11` scores than cell lines with `myc_amplification == 0`, after adjusting for lineage and screen covariates.", "kind": "novel"},
        {"id": "h16", "text": "Cell lines with both `myc_amplification == 1` and high `growth_rate_doublings_per_day` (top quartile, `growth_rate_doublings_per_day >= 0.964`) have more negative `dependency_RPL11` scores than all other cell lines.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h17", "text": "Higher `rnaseq_MYC_log2_tpm` is associated with more negative `dependency_DHX9` scores, and the high-MYC/high-growth subgroup has more negative `dependency_DHX9` than other lines.", "kind": "novel"}
      ],
      "analyses": [
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h15"], "code": "OLS: dependency_RPL11 ~ myc_amplification + C(lineage) + screen/culture/media/cas9/growth covariates", "result_summary": "Adjusted `myc_amplification` coefficient was -0.1043, supporting stronger RPL11 dependency in MYC-amplified lines.", "effect_estimate": -0.104298, "p_value": 4.29e-129, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h16"], "code": "Welch and adjusted subgroup test for I(myc_amplification == 1 and growth_rate_doublings_per_day >= Q75)", "result_summary": "The MYC-amplified/high-growth subgroup (n=2557) had unadjusted effect -0.1303 (p=1.10e-68) and adjusted subgroup coefficient -0.1084 (p=1.04e-46). The formal MYC-amplification by high-growth interaction was not significant (interaction -0.0151, p=0.105).", "effect_estimate": -0.108371, "p_value": 1.04e-46, "significant": True, "interaction_effect_estimate": -0.0151, "interaction_p_value": 0.105},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h17"], "code": "OLS: dependency_DHX9 ~ z(rnaseq_MYC_log2_tpm) + C(lineage) + screen/culture/media/cas9/growth covariates; subgroup high growth and high MYC RNA", "result_summary": "Each 1-SD increase in MYC RNA was associated with -0.0167 lower `dependency_DHX9` (p=1.45e-26). The high-growth/high-MYC subgroup had adjusted effect -0.0338 (p=4.24e-07), but the interaction was not significant at 0.05 (p=0.0878).", "effect_estimate": -0.016661, "p_value": 1.45e-26, "significant": True, "subgroup_effect_estimate": -0.033789, "subgroup_p_value": 4.24e-07, "interaction_effect_estimate": -0.0140, "interaction_p_value": 0.0878}
      ]
    },
    {
      "index": 7,
      "proposed_hypotheses": [
        {"id": "h18", "text": "Cell lines with high `growth_rate_doublings_per_day` (top quartile, `growth_rate_doublings_per_day >= 0.964`) have more negative `dependency_POLR2A` scores than lower-growth cell lines, after adjusting for lineage and screen covariates other than growth itself.", "kind": "novel"},
        {"id": "h19", "text": "Cell lines with high `growth_rate_doublings_per_day` (top quartile, `growth_rate_doublings_per_day >= 0.964`) have more negative `dependency_TMED10` scores than lower-growth cell lines, after adjusting for lineage and screen covariates other than growth itself.", "kind": "novel"},
        {"id": "h20", "text": "The subgroup with `lineage == prostate` and high `growth_rate_doublings_per_day` has more negative `dependency_TMED10` scores than other cell lines, beyond the broad growth association.", "kind": "refined"}
      ],
      "analyses": [
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h18"], "code": "OLS: dependency_POLR2A ~ I(growth_rate_doublings_per_day >= Q75) + C(lineage) + screen/culture/media/cas9 covariates", "result_summary": "High-growth lines had adjusted `dependency_POLR2A` coefficient -0.1044, supporting a strong growth-linked POLR2A dependency.", "effect_estimate": -0.104382, "p_value": 3.43e-180, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h19"], "code": "OLS: dependency_TMED10 ~ I(growth_rate_doublings_per_day >= Q75) + C(lineage) + screen/culture/media/cas9 covariates", "result_summary": "High-growth lines had adjusted `dependency_TMED10` coefficient -0.0370, a statistically strong but smaller growth-linked effect.", "effect_estimate": -0.036975, "p_value": 1.07e-24, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h20"], "code": "OLS subgroup and interaction tests for I(lineage == '"'prostate') * high_growth\", \"result_summary\": \"The prostate/high-growth subgroup had adjusted coefficient -0.0284 (p=0.0465) when continuous growth was also in the model, but the prostate by high-growth interaction was borderline and not significant at 0.05 (interaction -0.0313, p=0.0586).\", \"effect_estimate\": -0.028374, \"p_value\": 0.0465, \"significant\": True, \"interaction_effect_estimate\": -0.0313, \"interaction_p_value\": 0.0586}
      ]
    },
    {
      \"index\": 8,
      \"proposed_hypotheses\": [
        {\"id\": \"h21\", \"text\": \"In a systematic single- and pairwise-predicate heterogeneity screen, the most negative subgroup for "'`dependency_BRAF` is expected to include `braf_v600e == 1` cell lines.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h22", "text": "In the same heterogeneity screen, the most negative subgroup for `dependency_EGFR` is expected to include `egfr_amplification == 1` cell lines, with or without high growth-rate modifiers.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h23", "text": "In the same heterogeneity screen, the most negative subgroup for `dependency_ERBB2` is expected to include `erbb2_amplification == 1` cell lines.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h24", "text": "In the same heterogeneity screen, the most negative subgroup for `dependency_KRAS` is expected to include `kras_mutation == 1` cell lines.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h25", "text": "In the same heterogeneity screen, the most negative subgroup for `dependency_RIT1` is expected to include both `nf1_loss == 1` and `lineage == brain`.", "kind": "refined"}
      ],
      "analyses": [
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h21"], "code": "Systematic scan over 68 single predicates and all eligible pairs; Welch tests for dependency_BRAF subgroup vs complement", "result_summary": "The top BRAF subgroup was `braf_v600e == 1` (n=5574), effect -0.5552 vs the complement.", "effect_estimate": -0.5552, "p_value": 0.0, "significant": True, "search_scope": "all dependency outcomes; single and pairwise predicates from lineage, subtype, culture, media, mutation/CNA features, and high/low quartiles of continuous features"},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h22"], "code": "Systematic scan over 68 single predicates and all eligible pairs; Welch tests for dependency_EGFR subgroup vs complement", "result_summary": "The most negative EGFR subgroup was `egfr_amplification == 1` and high growth (n=964), effect -0.3526; the single `egfr_amplification == 1` predicate was nearly identical (effect -0.3486).", "effect_estimate": -0.3526, "p_value": 3.54e-149, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h23"], "code": "Systematic scan over 68 single predicates and all eligible pairs; Welch tests for dependency_ERBB2 subgroup vs complement", "result_summary": "The top ERBB2 subgroup was `erbb2_amplification == 1` (n=4890), effect -0.4321.", "effect_estimate": -0.4321, "p_value": 0.0, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h24"], "code": "Systematic scan over 68 single predicates and all eligible pairs; Welch tests for dependency_KRAS subgroup vs complement", "result_summary": "The top KRAS subgroup was `kras_mutation == 1` (n=11842), effect -0.3075.", "effect_estimate": -0.3075, "p_value": 0.0, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h25"], "code": "Systematic scan over 68 single predicates and all eligible pairs; Welch tests for dependency_RIT1 subgroup vs complement", "result_summary": "The top RIT1 subgroup was `lineage == brain` and `nf1_loss == 1` (n=329), effect -0.1397.", "effect_estimate": -0.1397, "p_value": 1.01e-12, "significant": True}
      ]
    },
    {
      "index": 9,
      "proposed_hypotheses": [
        {"id": "h26", "text": "In the systematic heterogeneity screen, `lineage == colorectal` and `apc_mutation == 1` cell lines have more negative `dependency_KIF18A` scores than all other cell lines.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h27", "text": "In the systematic heterogeneity screen, `lineage == prostate` and high `growth_rate_doublings_per_day` cell lines have more negative `dependency_TMED10` scores than all other cell lines.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h28", "text": "In the systematic heterogeneity screen, high `growth_rate_doublings_per_day` and high `rnaseq_MYC_log2_tpm` cell lines have more negative `dependency_DHX9` scores than all other cell lines.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h29", "text": "In the systematic heterogeneity screen, high `growth_rate_doublings_per_day` cell lines have more negative `dependency_POLR2A` scores than all other cell lines.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h30", "text": "In the systematic heterogeneity screen, `myc_amplification == 1` and high `growth_rate_doublings_per_day` cell lines have more negative `dependency_RPL11` scores than all other cell lines.", "kind": "refined"}
      ],
      "analyses": [
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h26"], "code": "Systematic scan over 68 single predicates and all eligible pairs; Welch tests for dependency_KIF18A subgroup vs complement", "result_summary": "The top pairwise KIF18A subgroup was `lineage == colorectal` and `apc_mutation == 1` (n=3925), effect -0.6899; adding high WNT and SMAD4 intact was tested in later refinement.", "effect_estimate": -0.6899, "p_value": 0.0, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h27"], "code": "Systematic scan over 68 single predicates and all eligible pairs; Welch tests for dependency_TMED10 subgroup vs complement", "result_summary": "The top TMED10 subgroup was `lineage == prostate` and high growth (n=621), effect -0.0533, but later regression showed this modifier was weak after conditioning on growth.", "effect_estimate": -0.0533, "p_value": 0.000112, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h28"], "code": "Systematic scan over 68 single predicates and all eligible pairs; Welch tests for dependency_DHX9 subgroup vs complement", "result_summary": "The high-growth/high-MYC RNA subgroup (n=3320) had effect -0.0595 for DHX9 dependency; a smaller squamous/high-MYC subgroup had effect -0.0656 but weaker p-value because of sample size.", "effect_estimate": -0.0595, "p_value": 2.48e-21, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h29"], "code": "Systematic scan over 68 single predicates and all eligible pairs; Welch tests for dependency_POLR2A subgroup vs complement", "result_summary": "The top POLR2A subgroup was high growth (n=12577), effect -0.1043.", "effect_estimate": -0.1043, "p_value": 1.01e-179, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h30"], "code": "Systematic scan over 68 single predicates and all eligible pairs; Welch tests for dependency_RPL11 subgroup vs complement", "result_summary": "The top RPL11 subgroup was MYC amplification and high growth (n=2557), effect -0.1303.", "effect_estimate": -0.1303, "p_value": 1.10e-68, "significant": True}
      ]
    },
    {
      "index": 10,
      "proposed_hypotheses": [
        {"id": "h31", "text": "The final best-supported subgroup for `dependency_BRAF` is `braf_v600e == 1`, with more negative `dependency_BRAF` scores than `braf_v600e == 0`; no tested skin-lineage enhancement is required.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h32", "text": "The final best-supported subgroup for `dependency_EGFR` is `egfr_amplification == 1`, with more negative `dependency_EGFR` scores than `egfr_amplification == 0`.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h33", "text": "The final best-supported subgroup for `dependency_ERBB2` is `erbb2_amplification == 1`, with more negative `dependency_ERBB2` scores than `erbb2_amplification == 0`.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h34", "text": "The final best-supported subgroup for `dependency_KRAS` is `kras_mutation == 1`, with more negative `dependency_KRAS` scores than `kras_mutation == 0`; no tested pancreatic-lineage enhancement is required.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h35", "text": "The final best-supported subgroup for `dependency_RIT1` is `nf1_loss == 1`, with `lineage == brain` acting as an enhancer that makes the NF1-loss subgroup still more negative.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h36", "text": "The final best-supported subgroup for `dependency_KIF18A` is `lineage == colorectal`, `apc_mutation == 1`, high `wnt_activity_score` (`>= 0.819`), and `smad4_loss == 0`, with much more negative `dependency_KIF18A` scores than all other lines.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h37", "text": "The final best-supported pattern for `dependency_TMED10` is a modest broad high-growth effect, with high `growth_rate_doublings_per_day` (`>= 0.964`) lines more negative than lower-growth lines; no strong lineage modifier was confirmed.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h38", "text": "The final best-supported pattern for `dependency_DHX9` is a modest MYC/proliferation-linked effect, with high `rnaseq_MYC_log2_tpm` and high `growth_rate_doublings_per_day` lines more negative than other lines but without a significant interaction.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h39", "text": "The final best-supported subgroup for `dependency_POLR2A` is high `growth_rate_doublings_per_day` (`>= 0.964`), with more negative `dependency_POLR2A` scores than lower-growth lines.", "kind": "refined"},
        {"id": "h40", "text": "The final best-supported subgroup for `dependency_RPL11` is `myc_amplification == 1`, with the `myc_amplification == 1` and high-growth subgroup showing the most negative raw subgroup contrast but no significant MYC-by-growth interaction.", "kind": "refined"}
      ],
      "analyses": [
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h31", "h32", "h33", "h34"], "code": "Consolidation of adjusted driver-gene main-effect regressions and lineage interaction checks", "result_summary": "Matched alteration effects remained the best explanation for BRAF, EGFR, ERBB2, and KRAS dependencies: BRAF V600E -0.5545, EGFR amplification -0.3489, ERBB2 amplification -0.4325, KRAS mutation -0.3095. Skin and pancreatic lineage interactions were not significant for BRAF and KRAS respectively.", "effect_estimate": -0.309546, "p_value": 0.0, "significant": True, "component_effects": {"braf_v600e_on_dependency_BRAF": -0.554513, "egfr_amplification_on_dependency_EGFR": -0.348920, "erbb2_amplification_on_dependency_ERBB2": -0.432533, "kras_mutation_on_dependency_KRAS": -0.309546}},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h35"], "code": "Adjusted NF1-loss regression plus NF1-loss by brain interaction", "result_summary": "NF1 loss had adjusted effect -0.0955 on RIT1 dependency, and the brain-lineage interaction added -0.0579 (p=0.00582).", "effect_estimate": -0.095464, "p_value": 6.13e-69, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h36"], "code": "Complete subgroup test and SMAD4 suppressor interaction for dependency_KIF18A", "result_summary": "The complete KIF18A subgroup had effect -1.0460 vs all other lines, while SMAD4 loss suppressed this dependency by about +1.04 units.", "effect_estimate": -1.045960, "p_value": 0.0, "significant": True},
        {"hypothesis_ids": ["h37", "h38", "h39", "h40"], "code": "Consolidation of growth/MYC dependency models for TMED10, DHX9, POLR2A, and RPL11", "result_summary": "High growth was associated with POLR2A (-0.1044) and TMED10 (-0.0370) dependency; MYC RNA was associated with DHX9 (-0.0167 per SD); MYC amplification was associated with RPL11 (-0.1043). Interaction tests for DHX9 high-MYC by high-growth and RPL11 MYC-amplification by high-growth were not significant at 0.05.", "effect_estimate": -0.104382, "p_value": 3.43e-180, "significant": True, "component_effects": {"high_growth_on_dependency_POLR2A": -0.104382, "high_growth_on_dependency_TMED10": -0.036975, "rnaseq_MYC_per_sd_on_dependency_DHX9": -0.016661, "myc_amplification_on_dependency_RPL11": -0.104298}}
      ]
    }
  ]
}

summary = """CRISPR dependency analysis summary for ds001_depmap

Dependency scores are interpreted on their native scale: more negative values indicate stronger dependency after knockout. I ran 10 propose-test-refine iterations using only the local dataset. The analysis combined adjusted linear models, within-subgroup contrasts, interaction tests, and a systematic heterogeneity scan over 68 single predicates plus eligible pairwise predicates for every dependency outcome.

The clearest main effects were matched oncogene dependencies. After adjusting for lineage, screen batch, culture type, serum, Cas9 activity, and growth rate, `braf_v600e == 1` predicted more negative `dependency_BRAF` by -0.5545 (p underflowed to 0), `egfr_amplification == 1` predicted more negative `dependency_EGFR` by -0.3489 (p=0), `erbb2_amplification == 1` predicted more negative `dependency_ERBB2` by -0.4325 (p=0), and `kras_mutation == 1` predicted more negative `dependency_KRAS` by -0.3095 (p=0). Apparent lineage enrichments for these outcomes mostly reflected driver prevalence: among BRAF V600E lines, skin lines were not significantly more BRAF dependent than non-skin lines (effect -0.0103, p=0.295; interaction p=0.282), and among KRAS-mutant lines, pancreatic lines were not more KRAS dependent than other KRAS-mutant lines (effect +0.0004, p=0.955; interaction p=0.818). EGFR-amplified brain lines and ERBB2-amplified breast lines were strongly dependent versus all other lines, but their effects were similar in magnitude to the corresponding amplification main effects.

RIT1 showed a different RAS-pathway pattern. `nf1_loss == 1` was associated with more negative `dependency_RIT1` after adjustment (effect -0.0955, p=6.13e-69). The NF1-loss brain subgroup was stronger (adjusted subgroup effect -0.1384, p=9.58e-13), and the `nf1_loss` by `lineage == brain` interaction was significant (interaction -0.0579, p=0.00582). This supports NF1 loss as the core RIT1-dependency feature with brain lineage as an enhancer.

KIF18A had the most structured subgroup dependency. `apc_mutation == 1` was associated with more negative `dependency_KIF18A` after adjustment (effect -0.1469, p=5.85e-180), and higher `wnt_activity_score` was also associated with stronger dependency (effect -0.0440 per SD, p=1.14e-113). The colorectal/APC-mutant/high-WNT subgroup had a very large effect (adjusted -0.8596, p=0). Refinement showed that `smad4_loss == 1` suppresses this dependency: within colorectal/APC-mutant/high-WNT lines, SMAD4 loss shifted KIF18A dependency upward by +1.0433 (mean -0.2557 with SMAD4 loss vs -1.2990 with SMAD4 intact; p=0). The final best-supported KIF18A subgroup is therefore `lineage == colorectal`, `apc_mutation == 1`, `wnt_activity_score >= 0.819`, and `smad4_loss == 0` (effect -1.0460 vs all other lines, p=0).

MYC and growth-linked dependencies were also present. `myc_amplification == 1` predicted more negative `dependency_RPL11` (adjusted effect -0.1043, p=4.29e-129). The MYC-amplified/high-growth subgroup had a larger raw contrast (effect -0.1303, p=1.10e-68; adjusted subgroup effect -0.1084, p=1.04e-46), but the MYC-amplification by high-growth interaction was not significant (p=0.105). Higher `rnaseq_MYC_log2_tpm` predicted more negative `dependency_DHX9` (effect -0.0167 per SD, p=1.45e-26). High-growth/high-MYC RNA lines were more DHX9 dependent (adjusted subgroup effect -0.0338, p=4.24e-07), but the interaction was not significant at 0.05 (p=0.0878).

The broad growth-rate signal was strongest for POLR2A. High-growth lines (`growth_rate_doublings_per_day >= 0.964`) had more negative `dependency_POLR2A` after adjusting for lineage and non-growth screen covariates (effect -0.1044, p=3.43e-180). TMED10 showed a smaller high-growth association (effect -0.0370, p=1.07e-24). The systematic screen surfaced a prostate/high-growth TMED10 subgroup (raw effect -0.0533, p=0.000112), but the prostate-by-growth interaction was borderline and not significant at 0.05 (interaction -0.0313, p=0.0586), so I treat TMED10 as a modest broad growth effect rather than a robust lineage-specific dependency.

The systematic heterogeneity search covered every dependency outcome. The top or best-supported patterns were: `braf_v600e == 1` for BRAF; `egfr_amplification == 1` for EGFR; `erbb2_amplification == 1` for ERBB2; `kras_mutation == 1` for KRAS; `nf1_loss == 1` with brain-lineage enhancement for RIT1; colorectal/APC-mutant/high-WNT/SMAD4-intact for KIF18A; high growth for TMED10; high MYC RNA plus high growth as a modest DHX9 marker; high growth for POLR2A; and MYC amplification, especially among high-growth cells, for RPL11. Overall, the dataset contains strong engineered-like matched oncogene dependencies, a highly specific APC/WNT/SMAD4-defined KIF18A subgroup, and broader proliferation/MYC-associated dependencies for general transcriptional or ribosomal genes.
"""

Path('"'transcript.json').write_text(json.dumps(transcript, indent=2) + '\\n', encoding='utf-8')
Path('analysis_summary.txt').write_text(summary, encoding='utf-8')
print('wrote transcript.json and analysis_summary.txt')
